urch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whitchurch, Shropshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Sandford, Dorset, England":"Sandford, Dorset, Anglie"},"da":{"1258–":"1258–Afdød","1258–Female":"1258–Afdød","1260–Male":"1260–Afdød","1256–1327":"1256–1327","1292–1347":"1292–1347","1301–1348":"1301–1348","1302–Male":"1302–Afdød","1304–Female":"1304–Afdød","1240–Male":"1240–Afdød","about 1292":"omkring 1292","Abt 1304":"omkring 1304","02 DEC 2003":"2. december 2003","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","1348":"1348","1347":"1347","1258":"1258","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1256":"1256","Moreton Say, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Moreton Say, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Moreton Say, Shropshire, England":"Moreton Say, Shropshire, England","Whitchurch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whitchurch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Sandford, Dorset, England":"Sandford, Dorset, England"},"nl":{"1258–":"1258–Overleden","1258–Female":"1258–Overleden","1260–Male":"1260–Overleden","1256–1327":"1256–1327","1292–1347":"1292–1347","1301–1348":"1301–1348","1302–Male":"1302–Overleden","1304–Female":"1304–Overleden","1240–Male":"1240–Overleden","about 1292":"circa 1292","Abt 1304":"circa 1304","02 DEC 2003":"2 december 2003","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","1348":"1348","1347":"1347","1258":"1258","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1256":"1256","Moreton Say, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Moreton Say, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Moreton Say, Shropshire, England":"Moreton Say, Shropshire, England","Whitchurch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whitchurch, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sandford, Dorset, England":"Sandford, Dorset, England"},"en":{"1258–":"1258–Deceased","1258–Female":"1258–Deceased","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1256–1327":"1256–1327","1292–1347":"1292–1347","1301–1348":"1301–1348","1302–Male":"1302–Deceased","1304–Female":"1304–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","about 1292":"about 1292","Abt 1304":"about 1304","02 DEC 2003":"2 December 2003","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","1348":"1348","1347":"1347","1258":"1258","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1256":"1256","Moreton Say, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Moreton Say, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Moreton Say, Shropshire, England":"Moreton Say, Shropshire, England","Whitchurch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whitchurch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Sandford, Dorset, England":"Sandford, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Say  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Saje</b>: nickname for someone with very dark, sooty hair, derived from the root of <i>sajast</i> ‘sooty’, or directly from <i>saja</i> ‘soot’.","West African (Liberia): from the personal name <i>Saye</i>, found among the Mano (Mah) people, denoting a first-born boy."],"variants":[{"name":"Say","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Sai in Orne or Say in Indre, France, perhaps so called from a Gaulish personal name <i>Saius</i> + the Latin locative suffix <i>-acum</i> (see also French name 3 below).","English: nickname, perhaps for someone who made or sold say, a type of woollen cloth, or for an habitual wearer of clothes made of this material, from Middle English <i>sai(e)</i> ‘say’ (Old French <i>saie</i>, from Latin <i>saga</i>, plural of <i>sagum</i> ‘military cloak’). See also   Sayer  .","French (southern): topographic name from <i>saix</i> (from Latin <i>saxum</i>) ‘rock’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example, Say in Loire, Saix in Tarn and Vienne, Le Saix in Hautes-Alpes, or Les Saix in Isère."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes de Saye was born in 1258, in Moreton Say, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Hugh de Saye. She married Lord of Sandford Richard Sanford in 1280, in Moreton Say, Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1258–":"1258–Surnud","1258–Female":"1258–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1256–1327":"1256–1327","1292–1